          "body": "Isaiah 11 opens with one of the Old Testament's most compressed images: a shoot springing from Jesse's stump. The power of the image depends entirely on what came just before. In 10:33-34, the Lord personally hews down the towering trees of Assyrian imperial pride — the forest falls. Now, from the cut-down family tree of David (reduced almost to nothing by Assyrian pressure and dynastic failure), a shoot springs. Jesse's name, not David's, is chosen deliberately: this King emerges not from the heights of royal Jerusalem but from the humblest point of the Davidic lineage — a farmer's household in Bethlehem. John Calvin observed that Isaiah 'goes back to the root of the family from which David sprang, as if David had never been born' — pointing to a fresh, direct work of God that bypasses the corrupted branches of the monarchy. The New Testament recognizes this imagery with precision: Matthew 2:23 sees the 'Nazarene' in the root *netser* of Isaiah 11:1; Revelation 22:16 has Christ call himself 'the root and the descendant of David' — descendent (shoot) and source (root) simultaneously. The stump is the right image for the condition of any human hope: apparently finished, organically dead to all appearance. The messianic promise is that God works precisely from stumps."
