          "title": "The second Exodus — gathering the remnant from the four corners",
          "body": "The chapter's final movement (vv. 11-16) is the practical outworking of the banner raised in v. 10. The Lord acts 'a second time' (*sheni*) — the first time was the Exodus from Egypt under Moses; this is the redemptive act that recapitulates and exceeds it. Eight named territories (Assyria, Egypt, Pathros, Cush, Elam, Shinar, Hamath, the islands of the sea) compass the entire known world — north, south, east, and west. The gathering is of both Israel (northern kingdom) and Judah (southern kingdom), and its first domestic consequence is the healing of the Ephraim-Judah rivalry that had divided the nation since the days of Rehoboam (v. 13). The healed nation then moves outward in strength against its former oppressors (v. 14 — not ethnic triumphalism but the restoration of the covenantal geography). The two great barriers to return — the tongue of the Sea of Egypt and the Euphrates River — are destroyed and divided as God destroyed and divided the Red Sea at the Exodus (v. 15). A highway (*mesillah*) runs from Assyria (v. 16) — the same word Isaiah uses in 40:3 for the highway in the desert prepared for the returning exiles, and which the New Testament applies to John the Baptist's ministry (Matthew 3:3). The new Exodus is not a figure of speech; it is the actual rescue of actual people from actual geographical locations, accomplished by the same God who dried the Red Sea, through the same kind of miracle, along a real road. The Messiah who fills the earth with the knowledge of the Lord (v. 9) is the same Lord who provides the highway home (v. 16)."
